// SOURCE: Source Files/Intergrations/Fusion Intergrations 1/Operator Manual.txt
// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Operator Manual: Fusion Vault v4.0This guide is for Security Operations (SecOps) personnel managing the Fusion Vault.1. The Dashboard ConsoleThe main view is your command centre.Secure Operations: This is where you trigger manual encapsulations.Input Payload: Enter sensitive text here. In production, this would be the raw bytestream.Initiate Fusion: Triggers the 50/50 logic. Watch the button state change from "Processing" to "Success".System Status: Monitors the health of the cryptographic engine.Entropy Pool: Must be "HIGH". If this drops to "LOW", key generation may block until the browser gathers more randomness (mouse movements).Resource Usage: Displays the CPU/Memory footprint of the Lattice math operations.2. Interpreting the Live FeedThe bottom panel displays the real-time heartbeat of the system.ColumnDescriptionTimestampISO-8601 time of the event.Process IDThe internal thread or worker ID (e.g., KRNL-01).TypeINIT (Handshake), KGEN (Key Gen), ENC (Encapsulation).MessageHuman-readable status.LatencyThe total execution time. PQC operations will typically show >10ms.3. Managing KeysNavigate to Configuration > Keys.Auto-Rotation: Default is 24 hours. Reduce this to 1 hour for high-security environments.Emergency Revocation: The "Danger Zone" allows you to invalidate all active session keys. Use this only if you suspect a server compromise.4. NotificationsThe Bell Icon (top right) captures asynchronous alerts.Blue (Info): System patches or updates.Amber (Warning): High latency spikes or entropy depletion.Red (Error): Failed handshakes or "Strict Mode" rejections.5. Getting HelpIf the system behaves unexpectedly:Go to the Help & Support tab.Check the "System Health" card.If "Fusion Engine" is not "Stable", click Contact Engineering.
